1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:05,870
In this video we are going to learn six design pattern with Mediator library.

2
00:00:05,900 --> 00:00:11,720
That means we will be logical sequence implementation using the mediator library.

3
00:00:12,290 --> 00:00:13,850
Mediator is a popular.

4
00:00:14,030 --> 00:00:20,720
Net library used to implement the mediator pattern, which is great fit for the sequence design pattern.

5
00:00:20,750 --> 00:00:27,500
It allows to send commands and queries to the appropriate handlers without coupling the sender to the

6
00:00:27,500 --> 00:00:28,220
receiver.

7
00:00:29,150 --> 00:00:30,020
In mediator.

8
00:00:30,020 --> 00:00:32,299
We have a I request interface.

9
00:00:32,299 --> 00:00:36,350
So both commands and queries are modeled as a message.

10
00:00:36,350 --> 00:00:43,100
The I request interface is used to define a request which can be either a command or query.

11
00:00:43,250 --> 00:00:48,080
The return type of the request can be specified as a generic parameter.

12
00:00:48,470 --> 00:00:54,980
After the I request interface definition, we should define the handlers for each command and query.

13
00:00:54,980 --> 00:01:02,000
We define a handler that inherits from the I request handler, t request, and t response, where the

14
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,400
t request is the type of the command or query, and t response is return type.

15
00:01:08,360 --> 00:01:12,320
So we can define custom I command and I query abstraction.

16
00:01:12,680 --> 00:01:19,070
So in order to make the distinction between the commands and the queries clearer, we can define two

17
00:01:19,070 --> 00:01:20,480
custom interfaces.

18
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:22,880
These are the I command and I query.

19
00:01:22,910 --> 00:01:28,130
Both interfaces can inherit from the mediators I request object.

20
00:01:30,350 --> 00:01:38,660
So in ASP.Net core application, using the mediator controllers or minimal APIs act as a entry point

21
00:01:38,660 --> 00:01:40,670
for handling Http requests.

22
00:01:40,700 --> 00:01:46,730
You can see in here Http request comes from the client and the mediator acts as an entry point.

23
00:01:46,730 --> 00:01:54,320
So instead of the implementing the business logic directly within the API action, these actions delegate

24
00:01:54,320 --> 00:02:00,410
the responsibility to mediator, and after that mediator sending the command and queries.

25
00:02:00,410 --> 00:02:08,479
When a controller or minimal API receives a request, it creates a command or query object and send

26
00:02:08,479 --> 00:02:09,500
it to the mediator.

27
00:02:09,500 --> 00:02:13,340
Mediator then dispatch this object to the appropriate handler.

28
00:02:14,510 --> 00:02:20,270
So if you look at the mediator pattern and pipeline behaviors, the mediator pattern is implemented

29
00:02:20,270 --> 00:02:20,570
by.

30
00:02:20,570 --> 00:02:27,680
The mediator library is particularly useful in a complex or enterprise level applications, where request

31
00:02:27,680 --> 00:02:31,070
processing often involves more than just business logic.

32
00:02:31,490 --> 00:02:38,210
In this kind of applications, handling a request might require additional steps like logging, validation,

33
00:02:38,210 --> 00:02:40,790
auditing, and applying the security checks.

34
00:02:40,790 --> 00:02:43,820
These are known as a cross-cutting concerns.

35
00:02:44,270 --> 00:02:51,080
Mediator provides a mediator pipeline where these cross-cutting concerns can be inserted transparently.

36
00:02:51,080 --> 00:02:57,680
These pipeline coordinates the request handling, ensuring that all the necessary steps are executed

37
00:02:57,680 --> 00:02:58,940
in the right order.

38
00:02:59,090 --> 00:03:05,630
So in mediator, we have a pipeline behavior and pipeline behaviors are used to implement cross-cutting

39
00:03:05,630 --> 00:03:06,290
concerns.

40
00:03:06,290 --> 00:03:08,240
You can see the image on the slide.

41
00:03:08,270 --> 00:03:16,880
Chúng bao quanh quá trình xử lý request cho phép bạn thực thi logic trước và sau khi handler thực tế

42
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:17,600
được gọi.

43
00:03:17,600 --> 00:03:25,280
Vậy đây là quá trình pipeline mediator trước khi xử lý hoạt động thực tế, mediator cho phép preprocessor

44
00:03:25,280 --> 00:03:32,090
hành vi hoặc post-processor hành vi mà bạn có thể sử dụng những hành vi này để triển khai cross-cutting

45
00:03:32,090 --> 00:03:32,840
concerns.

46
00:03:34,250 --> 00:03:37,430
Ở đây bạn có thể thấy vấn đề của microservices.

47
00:03:37,430 --> 00:03:41,990
Nó cũng được sử dụng để triển khai các cross-cutting concerns khác nhau.

48
00:03:41,990 --> 00:03:44,240
Cái đầu tiên là log behavior.

49
00:03:44,570 --> 00:03:48,290
Một hành vi ghi lại chi tiết về request xử lý.

50
00:03:48,290 --> 00:03:50,690
Và cái thứ hai là validation behavior.

51
00:03:50,690 --> 00:03:55,370
Đây là hành vi xác thực các request đến trước khi chúng đến handler.

52
00:03:55,370 --> 00:04:00,050
Vậy chúng ta sẽ sử dụng hai hành vi này khi triển khai issue của microservices.

53
00:04:00,050 --> 00:04:06,530
Và những hành vi này đảm bảo rằng mỗi request được xử lý bởi mediator trong ứng dụng được ghi lại và

54
00:04:06,530 --> 00:04:12,710
xác thực một cách nhất quán, và nó chứng minh cách các cross-cutting concerns có thể được quản lý hiệu quả

55
00:04:12,710 --> 00:04:17,000
sử dụng mẫu mediator và các pipeline behaviors của mediator library.

56
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:24,380
Vậy chúng ta có thể nói rằng sử dụng mediator trong các ứng dụng ASP.NET cung cấp một cách có cấu trúc và sạch sẽ để xử lý

57
00:04:24,380 --> 00:04:25,970
xử lý request phức tạp.

